September10 
<superScript attach="right" box="[988,1000,618,632]" fontSize="6" pageId="4">th</superScript>
, 1829
</collectingDate>
</date>
(
<figureCitation box="[1084,1152,621,646]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1661,1683]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,337,1640]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,337,1640]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Holotype of Monodelphis glirina (NMW B 2626): A) dorsal is only the dorsal view of the skin; scale bar = 10 mm. B) front and verse of the specimen label showing patches of the original label, with the Johann Natterer field number 125. Picture: A.M.R. Bezerra." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3713904" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3713904/files/figure.png" pageId="4">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), referred as the 
<typeStatus box="[1338,1436,621,646]" pageId="4">holotype</typeStatus>
in some publications (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Pine, R. H. &amp; Flores, D. A. &amp; Bauer, K." box="[456,637,657,682]" pageId="4" pagination="425 - 441" refId="ref8613" refString="Pine, R. H., Flores, D. A. &amp; Bauer, K. (2013) The second known specimen of Monodelphis unistriata (Wagner) (Mammalia: Didelphimorphia), with redescription of the species and phylogenetic analysis. Zootaxa, 3640 (3), 425 - 441. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3640.3.6" type="journal article" year="2013">
Pine 
<emphasis box="[513,570,657,682]" italics="true" pageId="4">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pavan, S. E. &amp; Voss, R. S." box="[649,875,657,682]" pageId="4" pagination="1 - 44" refId="ref8495" refString="Pavan, S. E. &amp; Voss, R. S. (2016) A revised subgeneric classification of short-tailed opossums (Didelphidae: Monodelphis). American Museum Novitates, 3868, 1 - 44. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 3868.1" type="journal article" year="2016">Pavan &amp; Voss 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</materialsCitation>
The 
<date box="[945,1128,657,682]" pageId="4" value="1829-09">September 1829</date>
date is present in 
<bibRefCitation author="Pelzeln, A. von" pageId="4" pagination="1 - 140" refId="ref8544" refString="Pelzeln, A. von (1883) Brasilische Saugethiere. Resultate von Johann Natterer's Reisen in den Jahren 1817 bis 1835. Uerhandlungen der Kaiserlich-KOniglichen Zoologisch-botanischen Gesellschaft in Wien, 33 (Supplement), 1 - 140. Available from: https: // archive. org / stream / brasilischesethi 00 pelz / brasilischesethi 00 pelz _ djvu. txt (accessed 1 February 2018)" type="journal article" year="1883">Pelzeln’s (1883)</bibRefCitation>
monograph on mammal specimens collected by Natterer in 
<collectingCountry box="[958,1026,693,718]" name="Brazil" pageId="4">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and this is the only 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Burnett" authorityYear="1830" box="[1290,1436,693,718]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1290,1436,693,718]" italics="true" pageId="4">Monodelphis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimen known from that locality. Presently, this specimen has pelage coloration, much of which is depigmented, showing an almost homogeneous faint grey ochre grizzled dorsal coloration, with lighter patches along the pre and post auricular region, and the ventral side is pale orange with base light-gray and pale orange tip (
<figureCitation box="[1245,1314,801,826]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1661,1683]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,337,1640]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,337,1640]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Holotype of Monodelphis glirina (NMW B 2626): A) dorsal is only the dorsal view of the skin; scale bar = 10 mm. B) front and verse of the specimen label showing patches of the original label, with the Johann Natterer field number 125. Picture: A.M.R. Bezerra." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3713904" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3713904/files/figure.png" pageId="4">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
